          %td egal [e.ˈgaːl]
          %td equal
          %td.arrow →
          %td egaltâ [e.ˈgaːl.taː]
          %td equality
        %tr
          %td fahil [ˈfaː.xil]
          %td easy
          %td.arrow →
          %td fahlitâ [fʌ.xli.ˈtaː]
          %td ease
        %tr
          %td neutral [new.ˈtraːl]
          %td neutral
          %td.arrow →
          %td neutraltâ [new.ˈtraːl.taː]
          %td
        %tr
          %td fedél [fə.ˈdɛl]
          %td loyal
          %td.arrow →
          %td fedéltâ [fə.ˈdɛl.taː]
          %td loyalty
        %tr
          %td créativ [kre.jʌ.ˈtiv]
          %td creative
          %td.arrow →
          %td créatvitâ [kre.jʌ.tfi.ˈtaː]
          %td creativity

    %p Some nouns with this suffix may appear to have no corresponding adjective in the language or have an unusual derivation. Such forms typically derive from Latin words ending in <i>-itās</i>, but where the base adjective was eventually lost or underwent a divergent evolution. Examples include <i>caltâ</i> [kʌl.ˈtaː] “quality” (no corresponding adjective#{footnote}) and <i>librtâ</i> [ˈli.brɪ.taː] “freedom” (expected **<i>librtitâ</i>).
    %p The form <i>-itâ</i> is also frequently, but not necessarily, used after stems ending in /r/. The vowel before the /r/ will typically drop in such circumstances.
